        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 12 letter writer argues that more time in school would improve student performance. Neither I nor most of my high school peers could withstand a 9-hour day or 11-month school year.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 12 letter writer argues that more time in school would improve student performance. Neither I nor most of my high school peers could withstand a 9-hour day or 11-month school year.</p>
        <p>The time left for extracurricular activities, like clubs and sports, would be drastically reduced. The proposed one-month summer vacation would prevent students from taking many jobs or internships, and these are the experiences that let students learn how the ''real world'' functions. True school reform will be accomplished only by programs that encompass every aspect of education.</p>
        <p>DAVID SINGERMAN  Bethesda, Md., July 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
